orrespondence with his wife Elfride to answer these questions as they relate to Heidegger and all thinkers vulnerable to the politics of their times. They focus on Heidegger's tormented relationship with his wife, with Hannah Arendt, and with numerous other women, bringing an unusual level of intimacy to his personal and intellectual worlds.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aNational socialism and philosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Deconstruction.2bisacsh1 aCassin, Barbara, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aReinhard, Kenneth.1 aSpitzer, Susan.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311063857840uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/badi1579640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231542241423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231542241/original  a978-3-11-063857-8  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK